#Text=CHRISTMAS CONCERT
#Text=It was several nights before Christmas , and all along the freeway , cars were lined up like a vast herd of red-nosed reindeer being led off to slaughter .
#Text=I glanced away from the sight and reached out to snap off the radio .
#Text=I 'd had far too much of the Messiah since Thanksgiving .
#Text=You 'd think a respectable classical station could think of something more original to saturate the airwaves with .
#Text=But I knew that even if I changed the station , I 'd get White Christmas , or Blue Christmas , or Dixie Christmas , or some other form of musical blasphemy .
#Text=Traffic moved along sluggishly , inching up a long , curving hill .
#Text=It was raining heavily -- one of those sudden tropical storms , only it was happening in a refrigerator .
#Text=I had the windshield wipers on full , but still I could hardly see the vehicle in front of me .
#Text=Along with every other irate father , uncle , brother , and son who was late for some engagement or another , I was in the fast lane .
#Text=I had gotten caught in a last-minute sales meeting , and I was going to be late for my daughter 's concert if the idiot in front of me did n't hurry up .

#Text=The offending car was a Jeep , jacked up on all fours with tires big enough to dwarf a road-grader , and had struts and shock absorbers and what-not sticking out all over the undercarriage -- a real useful piece of machinery for navigating the treacherous Silicon Valley freeways : when you see a car you do n't like , you just roll right over it .
#Text=The Jeep had one of those typical California vanity plates , held in place by a brass frame which , had I been able to read it in the dark , would have said " My other truck is a Mack . "

column1: #Text=The driver was pumping on his brakes continually , no doubt keeping time to some Country Christmas Hit Classic .

#Text=Lounging on top of this pinnacle of western automotive engineering was a Christmas tree , lashed with a couple pieces of thin twine -- probably on its way to a living room hung with paintings of nudes on black velvet , and soon to be littered with tacky country decorations and strings of popcorn .
#Text=The tree listed to one side , bobbing over the edge of the Jeep 's roof in time with the blinking brake lights .
#Text=The driver 's girlfriend was smooching up to him in the front seat -- I could see her outline through the back window , practically sitting in his lap ... maybe she was in his lap .
#Text=I started thinking they probably deserved to lose the whole tree .
#Text=They 'd have a real nice surprise when they got home without it .
#Text=I reached over to turn on the radio again , thinking the hourly excerpt from the Messiah might be over by then .
#Text=I should have brought a tape from home , but I 'd barely had time to change my suit .
#Text=Just when my eyes were averted for an instant , the Christmas-tree bedecked vehicle in front of me decided to drop its load .
#Text=I felt my car go bump , bump , and slammed on my brakes before I even looked up .
#Text=The car behind me skidded and swerved to one side , then leaned on his horn as if he 'd run into an iceberg .
#Text=I just hit the emergency lights and leaned on my own horn .
#Text=The guy in front , perhaps hearing the tooting chorus behind him , stopped just down the road , and like an idiot , put his Jeep into reverse and came hurtling back toward me .
#Text=He skidded to a stop and put on his emergency lights .
#Text=What kind of jerk ties down a Christmas tree so loosely that it flops off in the middle of a freeway ?
#Text=We were only doing twenty miles an hour -- in the rain , no less .
#Text=I thought I would have to get out and check the extent of the damage , and I was n't happy about slogging in the rain with my dress shoes on .

#Text=Hallelujah , the jerk stopped , anyway , so I could at least get the name of his insurance company -- I 'd already memorized his personal license number ( which does n't bear repeating -- I 'd always thought the DMV had standards of decency ) .

#Text=I hopped out , trying to pull up the collar of my overcoat even though it would n't quite cover my head , and started walking forward to have a few choice words with Mister Country Jamboree in the over-endowed automobile .
#Text=Of course , CJ ( as I then dubbed the driver ) bounded out of the Jeep and headed my way , tucking in his shirt as he walked .
#Text=One look at him , and I almost turned around and left -- CJ could have been Paul Bunyan 's twin brother .
#Text=He had the shirt to prove it , too : red and black lumberjack style checks , with the top three buttons undone , and chest hair that was thicker than my beard .
#Text=He also wore cowboy boots and wide red suspenders .
#Text=" Holy moley , mister ! " he yelled with a tone of real concern .
#Text=" You alright ? "
#Text=I was about to lay into him when his gum-chewing girlfriend appeared from behind , tucking herself into his armpit .
#Text=" Oh ! " she squealed , " Ah 'm so sorry !
